<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Christopher_Alexander.jpg" class="image" title="Christopher Alexander"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Christopher_Alexander.jpg/250px-Christopher_Alexander.jpg" width="250" height="188" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Christopher_Alexander.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Christopher Alexander</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Christopher Alexander</b> (born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1936-10-04"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="10-04"><a href="/wiki/October_4" title="October 4">October 4</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1936" title="1936">1936</a></span> in <a href="/wiki/Vienna" title="Vienna">Vienna</a>, <a href="/wiki/Austria" title="Austria">Austria</a>) is an architect noted for his theories about design, and for more than 200 building projects in <a href="/wiki/California" title="California">California</a>, <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a> and around the world. Reasoning that users know more about the buildings they need than any architect could, he produced and validated (in collaboration with Sarah Ishikawa and <a href="/wiki/Murray_Silverstein" title="Murray Silverstein">Murray Silverstein</a>) a "<a href="/wiki/Pattern_language" title="Pattern language">pattern language</a>" designed to empower any human being to design and build at any scale. In 1958 he moved to the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>, and has lived in <a href="/wiki/Berkeley,_California" title="Berkeley, California">Berkeley, California</a> from 1963 until the present. He is professor emeritus at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_California,_Berkeley" title="University of California, Berkeley">University of California, Berkeley</a>.</p>
